Pisticci has been my favorite restaurant in New York since it first opened during my grad school days around the corner at Manhattan School of Music. The menu has evolved about as much as I would want it to considering how in love I was (from day 1) with some of the staple dishes. It's very difficult for me to not order the Penne Pisticci with the Roasted Garlic Bread with Warm Goat Cheese and then follow it with the Berries & Cream for dessert. I have ordered many things over the years, but this is my go-to. And now that I am only able to go there once a year at most, I almost always order my go-to (because I dream about it weeks before). Service here has always been fantastic, friendly, and personal. The wines have always been sophisticated without being pretentious. The pricing has never gotten out of control. And the charm of the place has not been lost with both of the massive expansions they did, each time increasing their floor space and seating capacity by over 100%. It's a true NYC experience without the tourist crowds and always with a flavor of community because of the regulars and familiarity between the staff.  Restaurants come and go in NYC because of the high standards, and it delights me to no end that Pisticci has (deservedly) survived and grown over the last 18 years - not just in size, but also in their ethics as a business (now Green Certified).  If the owner is reading this, I'm the guy who parallel parked your SUV with your baby in the back seat on Claremont Ave. in 2002 when you were struggling to get in the spot. Haha! So happy for all your success!

What a wonderful little spot in Harlem!  I met with old friends there and had a wonderful dinner.  This place features REAL Italian food done very well.  A member of our group had a fig salad that was on special and looked great; another person had the artichoke, which was excellent; and I had the fennel salad which was wonderfully balanced and tasty.  For entrees one of us have the Maltagliati, which is a flat pasta with ricotta and lamb ragu, which she always gets and was great.  Another person had the Fettuccine Al Funghi, which was fettuccine pasta with a variety of mushrooms with truffle oil on it, a had a bit and it was outstanding!  I tried the spaghetti with meatballs and it was really good.  We had a cake that was like tres leches for dessert and sorbet--I'm not a big fan of cream, but the folks who were loved the cake; the sorbets were great.  On top of the food the waitstaff folk had a good sense of humor.  The vibe at Pisticci was great as well, it had a real cozy, hidden hometown gem kind of feel.  If you are around check it out, you won't be disappointed.

I took off a star because the service wasn't the best. I called in advance and was told that I couldn't make a reservation, but that if we were there in the next hour, we'd get a table. No table was available when we got there. Then when we sat down, we were immediately told that we needed to be done in exactly an hour and a half due to a reservation. We also ordered a dish and asked if we could make a change. We were told the change was fine, but then we were charged for it.  Overall, I'd still come back, as these errors may be due to Friday evening, but it won't become a regular spot.

We have eaten at Pisticci several times when we've been in the Columbia neighborhood   While the food hasn't been outstanding , it's been passable and the setting comfortable. Last night we returned to find mediocre food and abysmal service. My insalata caprice was good but the pasta had become hard well beyond al dente. I suspect it had sat under a heating lamp far too long. When we arrived and after we stood by the bar about 5 minutes, I asked the bartender if we could be seated. Turned out that the woman seated at the end of the bar was the hostess. She begrudgingly got up to take us into one room, then bring us back to the first room for a table. It didn't get any better. Too bad. I had liked the place but it's gone downhill.
